Taken together, martingale residuals are most useful for spotting influential subjects or a
nonlinear covariate relationship, while Schoenfeld residuals are the basis for the proportional
hazards test and for plotting a covariate's effect against time.

## Baseline hazard and predicted survival

Although the Cox model does not assume a shape for the baseline hazard, it can estimate one
after fitting. The baseline cumulative hazard, and the survival curve derived from it,
describe a reference subject.

::: {#16c055e5 .cell execution_count=8}
``` {.python .cell-code}
# Load data and build the response
lung = gw.load_dataset("lung", backend="polars")
y = gw.Surv.right(lung["time"], event=(lung["status"] == 2))

# Fit a Cox model with age and sex as covariates
cox = gw.CoxPH().fit(y, lung[["age", "sex"]])

# Retrieve the Breslow cumulative baseline hazard and implied survival
cox.baseline_hazard(format="polars")
```

