Each column is a subject from `newdata`, and each row is a requested time. The `type="lp"`
and `type="risk"` options instead return the linear predictor and the relative risk.

### Confidence bands and conditional survival

Pass `ci=True` to add a pointwise confidence band around each predicted curve. Every subject
then gains `_lower` and `_upper` columns, built from the standard error of the cumulative
hazard and matching R's `survfit` (which combines baseline-hazard and coefficient
uncertainty).

::: {#859f796c .cell execution_count=11}
``` {.python .cell-code}
# Add pointwise 95% confidence bands; each subject gains _lower and _upper columns
cox.predict(newdata, type="survival", times=[180, 365, 730], ci=True, format="polars")
```

